\cf0 These trees have significant benefits for temperature, rainfall mitigation and carbon dioxide storage.\
\
Ward 3B is one of the hottest wards in the City. It includes the east side of King Street, lined with parking lots and few trees, and neighborhoods with limited tree canopy. Near noon on July 2, when temperatures were soaring all over the City, the average surface temperature in Ward 3B was over 100 degrees. Some parts of King Street reached as high as 110\'b0. In contrast, the temperature in the woods that this project would impact was in the mid-80s. \
\
If left undisturbed, the 29 significant trees on this site will intercept 55,344 gallons of rainfall and help avoid 2,209 gallons of stormwater runoff. They will reduce atmospheric carbon dioxide by 4,729 pound per year, adding to the nearly 145 tons of carbon they have already stored.\
\
The trees on this site cannot be replaced. They provide significant benefits to the neighborhood. They are part of one of the few woodlands in the downtown area. They should be preserved and protected, not cut down.}